        "content": "<div id=\"1\"> <p>Lawyers for two of the people charged in connection with the Lac-MÃ©gantic train derailment say charges against their clients should be dropped.</p> <p>The lawyers, who represent train engineer Thomas Harding and rail-traffic controller Richard Labrie, say a report into the causes of the accident made public by the Transportation Safety Board last week showed negligence at the Montreal, Maine and Atlantic Railway and poor supervision of the railway by Transport Canada.</p> <p>âIt is now obvious that the charges against each of these employees should not stand. Continuing in this direction will not serve the public interest nor help to prevent such an incident from happening again,â lawyers Thomas Walsh and Marc-Antoine Cloutier said Thursday.</p> <p>Harding, Labrie and a third MMA employee, railway-operations manager Jean DemÃ¢itre, have been charged with 47 counts of criminal negligence causing death. MMA has also been charged with the same counts.</p> <p>Forty-seven people died in July 2013 when a runaway crude oil train derailed in Lac-MÃ©gantic, setting fire to the downtown core and spilling millions of litres of oil into the environment.</p> </div>",
