      {
        "content": "<div id=\"1\"> <p>MONTREAL – Scott Abramovitch and Lonny Dubrofsky first met two decades back, working, respectively, as a Montreal Expos bat boy and producer of the radio broadcasts of the teamâs games.</p> <p>The guys hooked up again seven years ago in L.A. to form a production company, perhaps appropriately called Breaking Balls Films. So it might stand to reason that their first major Hollywood production, The Calling (opening Friday), would be a horror story focusing on the tragic demise of the Expos from Montreal.</p> <p>Not quite. The Calling is a horror story, but in lieu of bats and balls, there are knives and guns and all manner of occurrences most foul. The Calling, starring Oscar winners Susan Sarandon and Ellen Burstyn, is a psychological thriller about the hunt for a serial killer with a Messiah complex at loose in the boonies of this country.</p> <p>Abramovitch and Dubrofsky produced the film, while the former bat boy also penned the screenplay, based on the novel of the same name by Inger Ash Wolfe.</p> <p>Abramovitch began his Expos stint in 1991 and dutifully picked up errant bats until 1998. âBut I realized by the time I had reached puberty, that wasnât going to be a career,â muses Abramovitch, 38, holding court in his parentsâ Hampstead home with Dubrofsky.</p> <p>For his part, Dubrofsky was up in the broadcast booth, working with legendary play-by-play caller Dave Van Horne. He conducted post-game player interviews and also produced Mitch Melnickâs show on what was then CIQC. âThose were truly wonderful days here,â Dubrofsky, 36, reminisces.</p> <p>In light of their roots, their film foray, delving deeply into Christian mysticism, is all the more surprising.</p> <p>âI just happened to stumble upon a positive review of the book,â Abramovitch says. âThen after reading it, I fell in love with it and bought the film rights to it. After 50 pages, I felt this was a movie that we should be making: a commercial project set in Canada and written by a Canadian.â</p> <p>And, yes, howâs this for a refreshing twist: Canada plays Canada. Though much of The Calling is shot in rural Ontario, action also takes place in B.C. and Quebec. And all impressively done on a rather paltry budget of $4.5 million.</p> <p>The subject of Christian mysticism was, clearly, novel to the guys. âSo we figured we could rely on the wisdom of director Jason Stone, but it turned out that he was Jewish like us,â Abramovitch reveals.</p> <p>âSo when ever we hit on complex issues while researching the script, we figured we could certainly rely on the wisdom of the author. But Inger Ash Wolfe was actually a pseudonym for the novelist Michael Redhill, who was also Jewish. So here we had all these Jewish guys working on a film dealing with Christian mysticism. Thank God we had Susan Sarandon, a Catholic very passionate and knowledgeable about religion.â</p> <p>Prior to launching Breaking Balls Films, Abramovitch, a lawyer who graduated Cum Laude from Boston College law school, worked as a staff writer on the Lion King prequel Tinkerbell and scripted Sleeping Beauty II: Once Upon a Dream, both for the Walt Disney Company. Among other script credits, he co-wrote the feature No Surrender, starring Mena Suvari, and penned and produced the TV pilot Prayer Hour, a satire of televangelists with Jason Priestley.</p> <p>Dubrofsky, who collaborated with Abramovitch on Prayer Hour, first made his mark producing the acclaimed feature film Die Mommie Die, which made its debut at the 2003 Sundance Film Festival and received a jury award there. Dubrofsky also has TV production credits on ER, Gideonâs Crossing and the live telethon America: A Tribute to Heroes.</p> </div>",
        "_id": "1",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<div id=\"2\"> <p>âWe decided we could work well as a team in our own production company,â Dubrofsky says. âScott had a couple of book properties he had in mind. We optioned and developed a few of them as screenplays, with The Calling being the first feature film project.â</p> <p>The film opens today in 20 select markets in Canada and the U.S., before being released wide throughout the continent next Friday. A solid story helps, but the star-power of a Sarandon â who plays the central character, a burnt-out police inspector â as well as that of Burstyn, Donald Sutherland and Gil Bellows, can go a long toward propelling a motion picture, too.</p> <p>âWe got such a great group of talent together, but we really lucked out with (Sarandon),â Dubrofsky says. âHer agent saw the script and said it would be great for her. And when she came on board, it was, literally, a snowball effect with all the other talent signing up. Who doesnât want to work with her?â</p> <p>Apart from Sarandon, the actor who really stands out is Christopher Heyerdahl, of Nikita and Twilight Saga fame. He plays the spooky Simon, the man with the Jesus complex.</p> <p>âOur greatest stroke of luck was casting him,â Abramovitch notes. âWe had someone else in mind for the role, someone who everyone loved, but we had to lose him because this was a Canadian production and we were limited to the number of Americans we could use.</p> <p>âSo there we were two weeks before shooting and we didnât have that role cast yet. One of the actors told us about Christopher. So I rushed down with a camera to audition him in Toronto, and two seconds into the audition, it was clear this guy was perfect.â</p> <p>Abramovitch and Dubrofskyâs next film collaboration has them on more familiar terrain. Alive and Kicking, based on a true story and to be shot in Montreal in October, is about a group of women, soccer moms, who previously had no involvement in sports but who decide to form their own team.</p> <p>âThey begin playing other womenâs teams who have been together for years and they initially get in way over their heads,â Abramovitch says. âIt has a certain Bad News Bears quality.â</p> <p>So when can we expect the definitive tale about the demise of the Expos?</p> <p>âWhat we have more in mind is a film about the resurrection of the Expos,â Dubrofsky is quick to respond.</p> <p>âYeah, I know, another movie about resurrection,â Abramovitch cracks. âBut I was in town last spring for the reunion at the Big O with the Mets and Blue Jays, and the support I saw from the city was just incredible.</p> </div>",
        "_id": "2",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<div id=\"3\"> <p>âYou never know. I was a bat boy for Dennis Martinezâs perfect game in â91 in Los Angeles. That was so magical. And that magic has remained with me ever since.â</p> <p>The Expos also served as an icebreaker in landing Sutherland for the part of the priest, much learned in Christian mysticism. Sutherland is also much learned in Expos lore, a mega-fan who took in as many home games as he could.</p> <p>âAnd if he couldnât make the games, he would call in, anywhere from his place in the Eastern Townships to wherever he happened to be working throughout the world, to have someone in the Expos office place the phone next to the radio or in the broadcast booth next to (Van Horne), and he would listen to the entire game,â Abramovitch points out. âNow thatâs some kind of dedication, not to mention one hell of a long-distance bill.â</p> <p>bbrownstein@montrealgazette.comTwitter: billbrownstein</p> </div>",
