        "content": "<div id=\"1\"> <p>The city of Montreal will hold public hearings this fall on how to handle new car-sharing services such as car2go and Automobile.</p> <p>The cityâs transportation commission will hold meetings on Sept. 11 and Oct. 2.</p> <p>Among other things, the commission will look at whether the new car-sharing services should be encouraged, with an official policy adopted.</p> <p>Automobile and car2go allow members to borrow cars off the street at any time, then return them anywhere within certain parts of the city. Members pay per-minute rates.</p> <p>Both Automobile and car2go have paid participating boroughs for stickers allowing parking in non-metered spots, including most residents-only areas.</p> <p>Automobile and car2go are different from older car-sharing services such as Communauto, which requires members to reserve vehicles, and pick up cars from and return them to designated spots.</p> <p>For more information, visit <a href=\"http://ville.montreal.qc.ca/commissions\">ville.montreal.qc.ca/commissions</a></p> <p><a href=\"mailto:ariga@montrealgazette.com\">ariga@montrealgazette.com</a></p> <p>Twitter: <a href=\"http://twitter.com/andyriga\">andyriga</a></p> </div>",
