        "shortcode": "[wrapper mobile=\"show\" desktop=\"show\" location=\"full_page\"]<img class=”wp-image-1095457 alignnone size-medium wp-image-1095457 alignnone size-medium” src=”http://new.nationalpost.wpdqa3.canada.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/19/2017/04/lab.jpg” alt=”” width=”300″ height=”225″ />[/wrapper]"
      },
      {
        "content": "Barrow says the town has received funding from the province and the federal government to do the design work and has completed the environmental assessment. &ldquo;So it&rsquo;s a project that&rsquo;s active in one sense, but has not been tagged as a funded project, which gives us dates and timelines as to when it happens.&rdquo; Richmond Hill aims to add 20,000 residents to reach 225,000 by 2031, so demand for a subway extension should grow, especially considering the provincial growth plan mandates building upwards rather than outwards. One of the condo developments in the area is Renaissance of Richmond Hill by Tridel, at Yonge St. and Major Mackenzie Dr. Tridel built its boutique building&rsquo;s 100-plus units larger because buyers were residents looking downsize and stay in the area. &lt;strong&gt;FULL WIDTH &ndash; IMAGE TEST:&lt;/strong&gt;",
