    "titles": {
      "main": "Beautiful and deadly: Live reptiles at the Canadian Museum of Nature will leave you in awe"
    },
    "status": "published",
    "content_elements": [
      {
        "height": 630,
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ],
        "type": "image",
        "width": 840,
        "title": "Image title",
        "_id": "1",
        "url": "http://wpmedia.ottawacitizen.com/2016/10/red-spitting-cobra-photo-by-joe-mcdonald1.jpg?quality=55&strip=all&w=840&h=630&crop=1"
      },
      {
        "content": "The red spitting cobra produces venom that can blind you, but don&acirc;t worry, it&acirc;s safely behind glass in the Canadian Museum of Nature&acirc;s newest exhibition, Reptiles: Beautiful and Deadly. This is the largest travelling reptile exhibition in the world and, along with an assortment of deadly and non-venomous snakes, it also features tortoises, turtles, lizards and an alligator. A total of 19 impressive reptile species are on view from Oct. 7 to April 8, 2017.",
        "_id": "2",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Visitors can gaze at these amazing animals up close in their recreated habitats. Many of them are mesmerizing, such as the Gaboon viper with its beautifully-patterned skin, or the wise-looking giant tortoises. They move slowly, or not at all. In short, they&acirc;re very good at staying still for the camera!",
        "_id": "3",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "The exhibition was created by Clyde Peeling&acirc;s Reptiland in Pennsylvania. On weekends at 11 a.m. and 2 p.m., a zookeeper from Reptiland will be available to answer visitors&acirc; questions and offer cool facts about the reptiles on display. For example, did you know that neurotoxins from snake venom have been used in medicine to help treat Alzheimer&acirc;s and Parkinson&acirc;s diseases? The reptile keeper has a wealth of interesting knowledge to share &acirc; and some myths to dispel &acirc; about these misunderstood creatures.",
        "_id": "4",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Reptiles: Beautiful and Deadly is not only visually stunning (and super cool!) but it&acirc;s also very educational. Several interactive components reveal the mechanics of different reptiles. Push a button and observe how retractable snake fangs work. At other stations, learn about skulls, shells, locomotion, venom and how to tell the difference between an alligator and a crocodile. You can also examine scientific specimens from the Canadian Museum of Nature&acirc;s own reptile collection, and see items that were seized from the endangered species trade.",
        "_id": "5",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Admission to this special exhibition is $6 in addition to the cost of general museum admission. (On Thursdays from 5 p.m. to 8 p.m., general admission is free).",
        "_id": "6",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Be sure to visit nature.ca for information about hours, admission, and other activities. The museum is active on social media, so follow on Twitter (@museumofnature), Instagram (museumofnature) and facebook.com/Canadianmuseumofnature.",
        "_id": "7",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<figure class=\"wp-caption post-img size_this_image_test align-center\" id=\"attachment_893786\"><img class=\"wp-image-893786 size-full\" src=\"http://wpmedia.ottawacitizen.com/2016/10/gila-monster-photo-by-joe-mcdonald.jpg?quality=55&amp;strip=all\" alt=\"Gila Monster\"><figcaption class=\"wp-caption-text wp-caption\"><span class=\"img-caption\"> Gila Monster</span> <span class=\"img-author\"> Joe McDonald</span></figcaption></figure>",
        "_id": "8",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<strong>Cool facts!</strong>",
        "_id": "9",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Here are just a few of the many interesting facts about reptiles. We really encourage visitors to explore the exhibition in person to get a full appreciation!",
        "_id": "10",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<ul>\n<li>What is a reptile? Today most biologists classify animals by their evolutionary family tree, an approach called cladistics. The animals that evolved an outer covering of dry, horny scales are called reptiles. Their living descendants include turtles, crocodilians, lizards, snakes and birds (feathers are modified scales).</li> <li>There are more than 10,000 species of reptiles in the world. In Canada, there are 54 species and sub-species.</li> <li>This exhibition focuses on the âcold-bloodedâ reptiles, which depend on outside sources of heat to warm their bodies. (The first known warm-blooded lizard, the tegu, can heat itself to as much as 10 Â°C above its surroundings, making it unique among reptiles.)</li> <li>Although turtles are an ancient group, the structure of the shell has changed little since the age of the dinosaurs. Scientists disagree about where turtles fit in the evolutionary tree of life.</li> <li>Snakes are lizards that have lost their legs, ear openings and eyelids â possibly ancient adaptations for an underground existence.</li> <li>More people die from bee stings each year than snakebites. In the United States, about 8,000 people receive venomous snakebites. Only nine to 15 of those people die.</li> <li>Most venomous snake bites in North America are from copperheads, water moccasins and rattlesnakes.</li> <li>Alligators, crocodiles, caimans and the gharial are the closest living relatives of birds. They have birdlike hearts, digestive tracts, ear canals, and rib cages.</li> <li>Alligators and other crocodilians are the âloud mouthsâ of the reptile world. Calls vary widely depending on species, age, size and sex. Some species can communicate over 20 different kinds of messages through sound alone.</li> <li>Chameleons change skin colour to express a mood or aid in camouflage. Tentacle-like chromatophores move pigments up and down through the layers of skin. The closer the pigment gets to the surface of the skin, the darker the animal appears.</li> </ul>",
        "_id": "11",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      }
    ],
