        "_id": "1",
        "url": "http://wpmedia.ottawacitizen.com/2016/09/for-laura-robin-food-column-coconut-vegetable-slaw-julie-o.jpeg?quality=55&strip=all&w=840&h=630&crop=1"
      },
      {
        "content": "Bon App&Atilde;&copy;tit recently released its list of the Top 10 best new restaurants in America. Bad Saint, a Filipino place in Washington, D.C., came in at No. 2, with the list maker raving that it&acirc;s &acirc;the kind of place I spend all year searching for.&acirc;",
        "_id": "2",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "But even that experienced food writer, Andrew Knowlton, admits that he didn&acirc;t know what to expect when ordering some menu items, so different were the mix of ingredients. Once delivered, he liked the dishes so much, he cancelled a&Acirc;&nbsp;later reservation at&Acirc;&nbsp;a different place he needed to try.&Acirc;&nbsp;He wanted more of Bad Saint&acirc;s tangy, fiery, subtly sweet flavours.",
        "_id": "3",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "This slaw recipe from Bad Saint features all those things: a flavour mix&Acirc;&nbsp;so different, I wasn&acirc;t sure what to expect, and then an addictive combination of colour and crunch,&Acirc;&nbsp;subtle heat and sweet relief.",
        "_id": "4",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "The method too is different than your ordinary slaw: you plunge&Acirc;&nbsp;all the vegetables briefly in boiling salted water, then pat&Acirc;&nbsp;them dry. I was worried about limpness, so did the full blanche technique, plunging the vegetables into boiling water, then ice water&Acirc;&nbsp;to stop the cooking. I&acirc;m not sure if the ice-water step was necessary, but the slaw couldn&acirc;t have been better.",
        "_id": "5",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "The Bad Saint chefs do advise that the vegetables can be cooked and the chile pur&Atilde;&copy;e made as much as a day ahead, then covered and chilled separately. (Keep the blanched purple cabbage away from the other vegetables and even your tea towels: it will stain.) Toss mixture together just before serving.",
        "_id": "6",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<div id=\"fsk_splitbox_1715\" class=\"  fsk_splitbox_1715\"></div>",
        "_id": "7",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<strong>Bad Saint Slaw</strong>",
        "_id": "8",
