    "origin_url": "http://ottawacitizen.wpdev5.canada.com/business/local-business/unhealthy-habits-are-killing-canadians/wcm/0213040c-4ce7-49f0-b4bb-a2aadf2f23b2",
    "status": "published",
    "titles": {
      "main": "Unhealthy habits are killing Canadians"
    },
    "content_elements": [
      {
        "title": "Image title",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ],
        "_id": "1",
        "url": "http://wpmedia.ottawacitizen.com/2016/07/smoking-a-person-smokes-a-cigarette-in-downtown-ottawa-on-se.jpeg?quality=55&strip=all&w=840&h=630&crop=1",
        "type": "image"
      },
      {
        "content": "Unhealthy habits, such as smoking and physical inactivity,&Acirc;&nbsp;contribute&Acirc;&nbsp;to about half the deaths in Canada every year and reduce life expectancy by six years, according to a new study led by an Ottawa&Acirc;&nbsp;scientist.",
        "_id": "2",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "The research, which measures the health burden of unhealthy behaviours, was published in the journal PLOS Medicine on Tuesday.",
        "_id": "3",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "&acirc;Unhealthy behaviours place a major burden on Canadian life expectancies,&acirc; said Dr. ",
        "_id": "4",
        "paragraph": "open",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<a href=\"http://www.ohri.ca/profile/DougManuelLab/profile\">Doug Manuel</a>",
        "_id": "5",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": ", senior scientist at The Ottawa Hospital and professor at The University of Ottawa. &acirc;This study identified which behaviours pose the biggest threat.&acirc;",
        "_id": "6",
        "paragraph": "close",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Those unhealthy behaviours &acirc; in order of the harm they do to a person&acirc;s health &acirc; are smoking, physical inactivity, poor diet and unhealthy alcohol consumption. The study found 26 per cent of all deaths in Canada between 2009 and 2010 were attributable to smoking, 24 per cent were attributable to inactivity, 12 per cent were attributable to a poor diet and 0.4 per cent were attributable to unhealthy alcohol consumption.",
        "_id": "7",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "The researchers also found that Canadians who were non-smokers, had healthy diets, were active and did not drink excessively had life expectancies that were 17.9 years greater than those with the unhealthiest behaviours. The research showed that many people had combined risk factors.",
        "_id": "8",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Manuel, who is also a senior core scientist at the Institute for Clinical Evaluative Sciences, said the findings underscore how unhealthy behaviours contribute to deaths. Progress has been made in recent decades getting the message out about the deadly impact of smoking, and smoking rates have steadily dropped in Canada. Ottawa, according to recent research, has the lowest rate of smokers in the country.",
        "_id": "9",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "But Manuel said other unhealthy behaviours, notably inactivity, are not improving.",
        "_id": "10",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Manuel said understanding the impact of unhealthy habits helps public health officials plan better. To do so, he and his team created an algorithm to analyze data from Statistic&acirc;s Canada&acirc;s Canadian Community Health Survey and the Institute for Clinical Evaluative Sciences.",
        "_id": "11",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Manuel said Canada has some of the best health data in the world, in part because so many people are willing to link their health survey information to their health outcomes, meaning their age of death can be recorded along with their health-related habits. That information makes Canada a good place for the kind of research his team is doing, said Manuel. But he hopes it will also be used around the world in countries that have similar population health surveys.",
        "_id": "12",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "The algorithm allows for a more precise way of measuring the impact of health problems on life expectancy. &acirc;In an era of big data, we should be moving beyond the old methods that have remained largely unchanged for the past 60 years.&acirc;",
        "_id": "13",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Manuel and his team have also created an online calculator to help Canadians estimate their own life expectancies based on habits and lifestyle choices. It can be found at ",
        "_id": "14",
        "paragraph": "open",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<a href=\"http://projectbiglife.ca/\">projectbiglife.ca</a>",
        "_id": "15",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": ".",
        "_id": "16",
        "paragraph": "close",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "In an age when many people use activity tracking devices to motivate themselves to move, the calculator provides a whole new level of motivation, said Manuel.",
        "_id": "17",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "&acirc;Fitbits don&acirc;t tell you when you are going to die.&acirc;",
        "_id": "18",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      }
