    "origin_url": "http://ottawacitizen.wpdev5.canada.com/business/local-business/canadian-investors-may-face-a-bit-more-difficult-second-half-to-2016/wcm/c34205da-25f2-4268-8e99-590c59ca1e0f",
    "status": "published",
    "titles": {
      "main": "Canadian investors may face “a bit more difficult” second half to 2016"
    },
    "content_elements": [
      {
        "title": "Image title",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ],
        "_id": "1",
        "url": "http://wpmedia.business.financialpost.com/2016/07/blackrock-story-1.jpg?quality=60&strip=all&w=620",
        "type": "image"
      },
      {
        "content": "Low interest rates and low investment returns have been a global story so far in 2016 &acirc; unless you happen to be investing in Canadian bonds and equities, which have done investors proud by international standards.",
        "_id": "2",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "But can buoyant gold prices and a stabilizing energy market continue to carry domestic investors through a possibly tumultuous world in the second half of the year? Stay tuned, says Kurt Reiman, chief investment strategist at BlackRock Canada.",
        "_id": "3",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "The Global Investment Outlook Midyear 2016, published by the BlackRock Investment Institute (BII), notes that the first half of the year involved a delicate dance between confidence in a strengthening U.S. economy and anxiety over the fallout from the United Kingdom&acirc;s &acirc;Brexit&acirc; vote to exit the European Union played out on a low-growth world stage.",
        "_id": "4",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "&acirc;It hasn&acirc;t been such a low-growth year if you&acirc;re in Canada,&acirc; says Reiman. &acirc;The S&amp;P/TSX Composite Index is up more than 20 per cent since late January [as of Wednesday July 20]. If you&acirc;re in longer maturity Canadian government bonds, you&acirc;re up in the high single digits and that&acirc;s not a bad start to the year. Canadians have also dodged most of the effects of Brexit so far.&acirc;",
        "_id": "5",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<div id=\"fsk_splitbox_9\" class=\" fsk_splitbox_9\"></div>",
        "_id": "6",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "The BII sees Brexit presenting an ongoing downside risk to global growth, while shaking investor confidence and depressing inflation expectations in the Eurozone. However, a cautious U.S. Federal Reserve could continue to reinforce low global interest rates over the long term, while reviving beaten-down emerging market (EM) assets.",
        "_id": "7",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "A possible rabbit in the hat is a rally in risk assets prompted by investors shifting out of cash and low-yield assets in search of higher returns.",
        "_id": "8",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "&acirc;The second half of the year may be a bit more difficult for investors,&acirc; says Reiman. &acirc;Canadian 10-year bonds are now at one per cent and price-earnings multiples are somewhat stretched. There may be a little room for Canadian stocks to outperform the U.S., but yield will now probably depend on economic growth being much better than in the first half of the year and also on earnings recovery.&acirc;",
        "_id": "9",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "However, Reiman notes that the recent stabilization of oil prices has been good for Canadian earnings.",
        "_id": "10",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "&acirc;If oil prices remain in the high US$40s, low US$50s range per barrel, it will quickly be reflected in third- and fourth-quarter earnings,&acirc; he says.",
        "_id": "11",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Canada, like other countries, is experiencing the waning effectiveness of monetary policy, which has been a key driver of asset prices. While experiments in fiscal stimulus planned for Canada, Australia and Japan may produce some local benefit, the BII says it isn&acirc;t counting on an international approach to fiscal stimulus required to drive broad global growth.",
        "_id": "12",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "The Canadian economy could also feel the waves of an Italian constitutional referendum by October, a contentious U.S. presidential election in November and a possible Brexit-fuelled recession in the U.K.",
        "_id": "13",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "How can investors fine-tune their portfolios to net stronger growth opportunities in a low-growth environment with a potential for volatility?",
        "_id": "14",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "&acirc;I would want to have some ballast in the portfolio to be on the safe side,&acirc; says Reiman. &acirc;I would want some exposure to longer-maturity government bonds and some gold. While the first half of 2016 was dominated by predictions that the U.S. Fed would raise rates, the effects of rising populism and political risk on financial assets may be the big story for the second half of 2016.&acirc;",
        "_id": "15",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<em>This material is not intended to be relied upon as a forecast, research or investment advice, and is not a recommendation, offer or solicitation to buy or sell any securities or to adopt any investment strategy. The opinions expressed are as of the date indicated and may change as subsequent conditions vary. The information and opinions contained in this post are derived from proprietary and nonproprietary sources deemed by BlackRock to be reliable, are not necessarily all-inclusive and are not guaranteed as to accuracy. As such, no warranty of accuracy or reliability is given and no responsibility arising in any other way for errors and omissions (including responsibility to any person by reason of negligence) is accepted by BlackRock, its officers, employees or agents. This post may contain âforward-lookingâ information that is not purely historical in nature. Such information may include, among other things, projections and forecasts. There is no guarantee that any of these views will come to pass. Reliance upon information in this post is at the sole discretion of the reader.</em>",
        "_id": "16",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<em>This story was was created by Content Works, Postmediaâs commercial content division, on behalf of iShares by BlackRock.</em>",
