        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<strong>THE GOLDEN HANGOVER<br></strong>",
        "_id": "10",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Last week, British diver Chris Mears ",
        "_id": "11",
        "paragraph": "open",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<a href=\"http://news.nationalpost.com/sports/rio-2016/the-mixed-zone-british-synchronized-divers-shock-china-vow-to-get-absolutely-ruined\" target=\"_blank\">issued a decree</a>",
        "_id": "12",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": ": To celebrate winning men&acirc;s three-metre synchronized gold, he planned to &acirc;get absolutely ruined.&acirc; Now, it appears a quartet of victorious U.K. cyclists have taken Mears&acirc; words as a rallying cry &acirc; or a duty.",
        "_id": "13",
        "paragraph": "close",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Britain&acirc;s Owain Doull lamented a crippling hangover on Twitter Saturday morning, one day after he and three teammates raced to gold in men&acirc;s team pursuit. It probably isn&acirc;t surprising that Doull, as he told one inquiring user, was in worse shape than any of his teammates &acirc;by a country mile&acirc;: Hours after winning gold, he posted an Instagram selfie with his medal, captioning the shot, &acirc;Time to get pissed with the boys.&acirc; Rare is the athlete who can summarize the Olympic spirit so eloquently.",
        "_id": "14",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<strong>BIG MEN CAN JUMP<br></strong>",
        "_id": "15",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Aurimas Didzbalis tips the scales around 94 kg, allowing him to compete in Olympic weightlifting&acirc;s third-heaviest class. Over the weekend, though, the Lithuanian showed off a burst of remarkable agility, pulling off ",
        "_id": "16",
        "paragraph": "open",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<a href=\"http://ftw.usatoday.com/2016/08/weightlifter-wins-bronze-celebrates-with-epic-backflip\" target=\"_blank\">one of Rio 2016âs best celebrations in</a>",
        "_id": "17",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": " the process.",
        "_id": "18",
        "paragraph": "close",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Knowing he had lifted just enough to earn himself a bronze medal, Didzbalis dropped the bar, clapped his hands, drew a circle in the air and uncorked a clean backflip, transitioning seamlessly into a screaming biceps flash. For good measure, Didzbalis then pumped the front of his Lithuania jersey, showing everyone exactly who the medal &acirc; and the theatrics &acirc; were for.",
        "_id": "19",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
