      {
        "content": "<div id=\"main\" class=\"l-main\"> <article id=\"post-857983\" class=\"l-article post-857983 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-columnists tag-kelly-egan tag-kitchissippi tag-sharon-boddy tag-trailhead\"><div class=\"entry-content p402_premium\"> <figure class=\"align-none wp-caption post-img\" id=\"post-859425media-859425\"><img class=\"wp-post-image\" src=\"http://wpmedia.ottawacitizen.com/2016/08/trail-head.jpeg?quality=55&amp;strip=all&amp;w=840&amp;h=630&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"Trailhead store at Scott and McRae in Ottawa Monday July 18, 2016. Tony Caldwell\" width=\"840\" height=\"630\"><figcaption class=\"wp-caption-text\"><span class=\"img-caption\">The Trailhead store at Scott and McRae streets will be torn down.</span> <span class=\"img-author\">Tony Caldwell / Tony Caldwell</span></figcaption></figure><div class=\"article-actions\">\n<a href=\"http://ottawacitizen.com/opinion/columnists/boddy-a-kitchissippi-crank-responds-to-our-columnist#\" class=\"icon-share\">Share</a> <a href=\"http://ottawacitizen.com/opinion/columnists/boddy-a-kitchissippi-crank-responds-to-our-columnist#\" class=\"icon-adjust\">Adjust</a> <a href=\"http://ottawacitizen.com/opinion/columnists/boddy-a-kitchissippi-crank-responds-to-our-columnist#\" class=\"icon-comment\">Comment</a> <a class=\"icon-print\">PrintÂ Â Â Â  </a>\n</div> <div> <p><em><strong>Rebuttal:</strong>Â <a href=\"http://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/egan-million-dollar-piles-and-the-path-trailhead-was-inadvertently-blazing\">Million-dollar piles and the path Trailhead was inadvertently blazing, July 18:</a></em></p> <p>Thanks, columnist Kelly Egan, for putting me squarely into the camp of âbitter old bastards.â</p> <p>Iâm a lifelong Kitchissippian who doesnât own a car. Iâve walked and cycled this area for decades and know my neighbourhood very well. I know where the short cuts are, where to pick raspberries, and that the man in the hat on the mural of Tivoliâs exterior wall is based on a real person.</p> <p>Iâve been witness to the changes Kitchissippi has undergone in the last 20 years, ever since Mountain Equipment Co-Op moved in. Soon after that, store owners started complaining about increased rents. Today, many of those independently run businesses are gone.</p> <p>Then the steel-and-glass houses arrived, often with two houses replacing a single home. The new houses are not unattractive, but they bear no resemblance to our red-brick past. I thought the city was supposed to ensure that new developments kept in character with the neighbourhood, but nowhere in Ottawa has this been more ignored than in Kitchissippi. Instead, the city hides behind the theory of intensification.</p> <div id=\"fsk_splitbox_1715\" class=\" fsk_splitbox_1715\"></div> <p>Intensification makes more efficient use of infrastructure, land and other services, if done right. In transit-rich Kitchissippi, intensification was supposed to encourage people to drive less. Unfortunately, some homeownersÂ âÂ with two, three or even four vehiclesÂ âÂ didnât get that memo.</p> <p>Kitchissippi is a desirable neighbourhood. Itâs close to downtown, the river, itâs walkable and cyclable; there are schools, stores and services, parks and mature trees. Itâs always been that way. Even 40Â years ago, Kitchissippi had everything you needed on a daily or weekly basis.</p> <p>What has changed is that a relatively affordable neighbourhood is now the playground for profit-at-any-cost, unimaginative developers, and the reasons that people moved here in the first place are being stripped away.</p> <p>Some of these new homes may soon have flooding issues. When green space is paved over to build homes right to the property line, eventually the landâs ability to absorb water from increasingly extreme storms will be compromised. Water has to go somewhere and many of Ottawaâs storm sewers are not up to the task.</p> <p>Kitchissippiâs neighbourhoods have always been prosperous, but the most expensive properties were traditionally surrounded by lower and middle-class homes and apartments. If you couldnât afford a house on Island Park, you could afford a house nearby and enjoy all the same community benefits as your wealthier neighbours.</p> <p>My house cost less than $150,000 in 1993; itâs now worth three times that. People tell me I should be grateful for the equity, but equity only counts when youâre selling; if you donât plan on moving, equity only means higher property taxes. So why exactly should I fall on my knees in gratitude when my taxes have risen more than 50 per cent in the last 15 years but my services have stayed the same or even been reduced?</p> <p>One would think that the city would want people to stay in one place. Isnât that what makes a community? A community is not a grocery store, or 6,000 new condo units, or even a bigger, better transit system. A community is its people. And communities will always need bitter old bastards like me to make sure that history isnât lost beneath coffee grounds, discarded yoga mats or last yearâs fleece fashions.</p> <p><em><strong>Sharon Boddy</strong> is a freelance editor and writer.</em></p> </div> </div> </article>\n</div>",
