    "content_elements": [
      {
        "content": "<div class=\"story-content\"> <div id=\"page1\"> <div> <p>TORONTO â The crowd had gathered by the shops and restaurants on Main Street, smartphones in hand, jockeying to capture digital creatures. Suddenly, four shots whizzed by.</p> <p>The group was playing Pokemon Go and the woman on the rooftop, armed with a pellet gun, was allegedly aiming at them.</p> <p>Police in Newmarket, Ont. say Patricia Champagne, 29, climbed onto the roof of her two-storey apartment building late Saturday, and fired at least four pellets down onto the road.</p> <p>Champagne did not tell<a href=\"http://ottawacitizen.wpdev5.canada.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2016/07/AzureBentley1.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-134462\" src=\"http://ottawacitizen.wpdev5.canada.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2016/07/AzureBentley1.jpg\" alt=\"AzureBentley1\" width=\"1529\" height=\"817\"></a> officers why she did this, Const. Andy Pattenden of York Regional Police (YPR) said Monday. But even if Pokemon Go, an augmented-reality mobile game released this month, did not provoke her actions, it appears to have played a part.</p> <p>âThereâs a couple of areas in York Region where weâve seen a significant increase in the number of people out on the streets and gathering in certain areas, playing this game,â Pattenden said.</p> <p>That includes Main Street South in Newmarket, a cluster of stores, restaurants and residential buildings, where bystanders told police they were playing Pokemon Go Saturday night. At about 10:30 p.m., officers responded to reports of a woman âshooting a handgun-style pellet gunâ from a nearby roof, according to a YRP release.</p> <p>None of the shots connected, and no one was injured. Officers entered the apartment complex, arrested Champagne and confiscated the pellet gun.</p> <p>âIâm gathering that there were probably quite a few people in the area at the time,â Pattenden said, adding he didnât know how close any of the pellets came to striking anyone.</p> <p>Police charged Champagne with assault with a weapon and possession of a weapon for a dangerous purpose. She was released from custody and is scheduled to appear in court Aug. 26.</p> <p>Pattenden said York police have received a âsignificantâ number of calls â likely in the dozens â this month from residents concerned about large, impromptu gatherings of people. Many have turned out to be PokÃ©mon Go players. Pattenden said no one has been charged for playing the game.</p> <p>âTo date, everythingâs been done in a lawful manner,â he said. âWe havenât received reports of people trespassing or causing any issues.â</p> <p><img id=\"storyphoto\" class=\"wp-post-image\" title=\"Pokemon Go players gather at a park in Los Angeles. Similar congregations have been happening around the world because of the popular game.\" src=\"http://www.ottawacitizen.com/news/national/cms/binary/12082254.png?size=sw620x65\" alt=\"Pellet gun-toting Ontario woman charged with firing at Pokemon Go players\"></p> </div> </div> </div>",
