    "origin_url": "http://ottawacitizen.wpdev5.canada.com/news/local-news/crown-to-abandon-charges-against-senator-patrick-brazeau-on-wednesday/wcm/ee699858-dbdb-4fba-9168-1a6e7bcde019",
    "status": "published",
    "titles": {
      "main": "Crown to abandon charges against Senator Patrick Brazeau on Wednesday"
    },
    "content_elements": [
      {
        "content": "Two and a half years after Sen. Patrick Brazeau was charged with fraud and breach of trust related to living expenses billed to the Senate, prosecutors have abandoned their case against him, the Ottawa Citizen&Acirc;&nbsp;has learned.",
        "_id": "1",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Assistant Crown attorneys assigned to the case are expected to officially abandon the case on Wednesday morning in Court Room No. 32 before Ontario Superior Court Justice Robert Maranger. The proceedings are scheduled to start at 10 a.m. at the Elgin Street courthouse.",
        "_id": "2",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Prosecutors have folded their case after conceding they didn&acirc;t have a reasonable prospect of conviction after reviewing the RCMP case against Brazeau.",
        "_id": "3",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "The fraud and breach of trust charges stemmed from&Acirc;&nbsp;disputed Senate housing expense claims for his primary residence in Maniwaki.",
        "_id": "4",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "The legal victory for Brazeau, 41, follows the resounding acquittal of Sen. Mike Duffy, who was defended by top lawyer Donald Bayne.",
        "_id": "5",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "While Brazeau was facing similar charges to Duffy, he was only facing two charges &acirc; fraud and breach of trust &acirc; stemming from a single alleged crime. The breach of trust charge was added because Brazeau was in public office at the time.",
        "_id": "6",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Brazeau was appointed to the Senate on the advice of then-Prime Minister Stephen Harper in 2009. He was suspended in November 2013 over questions about his housing expenses. Brazeau has told the Ottawa Citizen&Acirc;&nbsp;in the past that he provided all requested paperwork and was granted permission for his claims before he submitted them.",
        "_id": "7",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Brazeau is still suspended from the Senate but would like&Acirc;&nbsp;to return,&Acirc;&nbsp;he has told the Citizen.",
        "_id": "8",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "The Senate has withheld Brazeau&acirc;s salary since his suspension&Acirc;&nbsp;in an effort to recover&Acirc;&nbsp;the $49,000 in questionable expenses he is alleged to owe the upper chamber.",
        "_id": "9",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Reached late Tuesday afternoon, the senator declined to comment.",
        "_id": "10",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Brazeau is also facing a charge of refusing a breathalyzer&Acirc;&nbsp;after an incident in L&acirc;Ange-Gardien, east of Gatineau, in early April. He next court date in that case is Oct. 26.",
        "_id": "11",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Last year, Brazeau&Acirc;&nbsp;pleaded guilty to an assault charge &acirc; a charge of sexual assault in the same case was dropped &acirc; and he received an unconditional discharge.",
        "_id": "12",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "If the fraud and breach of trust charges against Brazeau are dropped Wednesday, they&acirc;ll be the last at play in the senate expenses scandal. It began in November 2012 when the Senate&acirc;s internal economy committee tasked three senators with reviewing Brazeau&acirc;s housing allowance.",
        "_id": "13",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Charges were withdrawn against former senator Mac Harb in May, the day after the RCMP announced that Sen. Pamela Wallin would not be charged in relation to her travel expense claims and the month after Duffy&acirc;s acquittal.",
        "_id": "14",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "In an exclusive interview with Postmedia during a May canoe trip on the Gatineau River, Brazeau spoke at length about&Acirc;&nbsp;a January suicide attempt, and said that he&acirc;s glad to be alive and to have the support of his family. Brazeau, once a rising star as head of the Congress of Aboriginal Peoples, said that he is in therapy after months in rehab but &acirc;I&acirc;m still not out of the woods yet.&acirc;",
        "_id": "15",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "gdimmock@postmedia.com",
        "_id": "16",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
