    "titles": {
      "main": "Wine drinking hits new heights in Canada"
    },
    "content_elements": [
      {
        "content": "<div> <p>Wine consumption figures are published every now and again, giving usÂ per capita figures for each country and trends over time. Are weÂ drinking more or less wine, and how does our consumption compare that ofÂ other countries?</p> <p>Itâs clear that Canadians drink far more wine these days than 10 or 20Â years ago. Wine has become part of lifestyle for many people, and theÂ scores of web sites, books, blogs, newspaper columns, and apps reflectÂ wide interest. Canadians now drink 15 litres of wine a head each year.Â Thatâs 20 bottles a year â about a bottle and a half a month â and itâsÂ twice what we were drinking in 1990.</p> <p>Americans drink less, 11 litres, but citizens of some countries drinkÂ much more. The French down 43 litres a year, the Italians 36 litres, andÂ Germans 25 litres. Coming up quickly are Australians and New Zealanders,Â with 21 litres each. Some (like Canada) are increasing, but big consumers such as the French, Italians, and Spanish, having beenÂ drinking steadily less wine since the 1960s.</p> <p>The worldâs biggest wine-drinkers? The people who live in the VaticanÂ City top the table, with 50 litres each per year (just over a bottle aÂ week). And people on small, isolated islands seem to find solace in wineÂ bottles: St Helena, in the south Atlantic, and Norfolk Island, between Australia and New Zealand, are in the top five.</p> <p>The problem with per capita figures is that they include everyone:Â children, women and men. If you took out people under 15, youâd have aÂ higher rate of wine consumption. And within the adult population, someÂ groups drink more than others. Men drink more than women, poorer peopleÂ drink less wine than the better-off, and older people drink more thanÂ younger people.</p> <p>This accounts to some extent for all the wine consumed in the VaticanÂ City. They are nearly all adults, with a majority of men. Iâm surprisedÂ their wine consumption isnât higher. A bottle of wine a week isnât evenÂ a small glass a day.</p> <p>In fact, âper capita consumptionâ is misleading: itâs really the amountÂ of wine available to everyone. Consumption is much more restricted. ForÂ one thing, many adults never drink: about a third of Americans and aÂ fifth of Italians and Canadians. Obviously, the more non-drinkers thereÂ are, the more wine is available to a smaller group of adults.</p> <p>How does your wine consumption fit into the picture? If you drink aÂ bottle a week, youâre up there with the citizens of the Vatican. If youÂ drink two bottles a week â a glass or two a day â youâre well up thereÂ and might find retiring to a remote island very congenial.</p> <figure class=\"wp-caption post-img size_this_image_test aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_627462\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-627462\" src=\"http://wpmedia.ottawacitizen.com/2015/09/left-to-right-goats-do-roam-villa-maria-pinot-noir-guard.jpeg?quality=55&amp;strip=all\" alt=\"Goats do Roam, Villa Maria Pinot Noir, Guardian Red Blend, Ring Bolt Cabernet Sauvignon\"><figcaption class=\"wp-caption-text wp-caption\"><span class=\"img-caption\"> Goats Do Roam Red, Villa Maria Pinot Noir, Guardian Reserve Blend, Ringbolt Cabernet Sauvignon</span> <span class=\"img-author\"> Wayne Cuddington / Ottawa Citizen</span> </figcaption></figure><h3>Goats do Roam Red 2014</h3> <p>From South Africaâs Western Cape region, this dry, shiraz-dominant blendÂ delivers concentrated and nicely layered flavours right through, cleanÂ and fresh acidity, and light tannins. It goes well with barbecued redÂ meats and sausages. 14-per cent alcohol; $12.95 (718940)</p> <h3>Villa Maria Pinot Noir 2013</h3> <p>This is a quite richly flavoured pinot thatâs very versatile with food.Â Try it with chicken, pork, and many red meats. The flavours are wellÂ defined with good complexity, and theyâre supported by fresh acidity andÂ framed by moderate tannins. 13.5-per cent alcohol; $19.95 (146548)</p> <h3>Guardian Reserve Blend 2012</h3> <p>Made from carmenÃ¨re, cabernet sauvignon, merlot, and cabernet franc,Â this Chilean red is dry, fruity, and very approachable. The flavours areÂ quite plush, the acidity is good, and the tannins easy-going. Drink itÂ with burgers, ribs, and sausages. 14-per cent alcohol; $13.60 (392787)</p> <h3>Ringbolt Cabernet Sauvignon 2013</h3> <p>This medium-full bodied cab from Margaret River in Western AustraliaÂ delivers quality and value vintage after vintage. Look for solid,Â focused flavours, excellent fruit-acid balance, and ripe tannins. ItâsÂ for grilled red meats. 13.5-per cent alcohol; $21.95 (606624, Vintages<br> Essential)</p> <p><a href=\"mailto:rod@rodphillipsonwine.com\" target=\"_blank\">rod@rodphillipsonwine.com</a><br><a href=\"http://twitter.com/rodphillipswine\" target=\"_blank\">twitter.com/rodphillipswine</a></p> </div>",
