    "origin_url": "http://ottawacitizen.wpdev5.canada.com/life/food/recipes/what-to-eat-delicious-salmon-easy-and-ready-in-half-an-hour/wcm/9a70cc46-57b9-4c4a-9f2e-25d759711738",
    "status": "published",
    "titles": {
      "main": "What To Eat: Delicious salmon, easy and ready in half an hour"
    },
    "content_elements": [
      {
        "content": "<div> <p>Iâve made this recipe several times and Iâve loved it more each time. The crumb coating gets crispy and rich, but with bright notes of lemon zest and Dijon. Underneath, the salmon remains moist, succulent and meltingly tender.</p> <p>Itâs dead-easy to make and, if youâre making it for guests, you can even make the crumb coating in advance, refrigerate it covered in bowl, thenÂ sprinkle it on to the mustard-coated fish just before cooking.</p> <p>The recipe is a slightly adapted version of one from Ina Garten. It works well with roasted baby potatoes (roll them in a little olive oil and salt and pepper); just preheat the oven to 425 F (220 C)Â aboutÂ 45 minutes before you want to eat and start the potatoes before the salmon. It also makes a great Easter entrÃ©e, with roast asparagus topped with a vinaigrette.</p> <p><strong>Panko-Crusted Salmon</strong></p> <p><strong>Makes:</strong> 4 servings</p> <p><strong>Preparation time:</strong> about 25Â minutes</p> <p>2/3 cup (160 mL) panko (Japanese dried bread crumbs)</p> <p>2 tbsp (30 mL) minced fresh parsley</p> <p>1 tsp (5 mL) grated lemon zest</p> <p>Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper</p> <p>3 tbsp (45 mL) melted butter, divided</p> <p>1Â½Â to 2 lb (680 to 900 g) piece salmon fillet, skin on</p> <p>1Â½Â tbsp (22.5 mL) Dijon mustard</p> <p>2 tbsp (20 mL) vegetable oil</p> <p>Lemon wedges for serving</p> <ol>\n<li>Preheat oven to 425 F (220 C).</li> <li>In a small bowl, mix together the panko crumbs, parsley, lemon zest,Â Â½ tsp (2.5 mL) salt andÂ Â½ tsp (2.5 mL) pepper. Melt 3 tbsp (45 mL)Â butter in a glass measuring cup in microwave; drizzle about half the melted butter over the crumbs, stirring until crumbs are evenly coated. Set aside crumbs and remaining melted butter.</li> <li>Place the salmon fillet, skin side down, on a board. Spread the top with mustard and then sprinkle generously with salt and pepper. Press the panko mixture thickly on top of the mustard. The mustard will help the panko adhere.</li> <li>Heat the vegetable oil over medium-high heat in a 12-inch (30-cm) cast-iron skillet or other large, heavy, ovenproof pan. When the oil is very hot, add the salmon, skin side down, and sear for 3 to 4 minutes, without turning, until the skin is brown and crisp.</li> <li>Transfer the pan to the hot oven for 5 to 7 minutes, until the salmon is almost cooked. Drizzle the remaining butter over the top of the crumbs and broil for just a few minutes, until some of the crumbs are browned and crispy. Remove from the oven and allow to rest for 5 to 10 minutes. Serve the salmon with lemon wedges.</li> </ol>\n</div>",
