    "titles": {
      "main": "Rideau Centre remodel"
    },
    "content_elements": [
      {
        "content": "<div> <p>The massive $360-million expansion of the CF Rideau Centre in downtown Ottawa officially opens to the public ThursdayÂ after 36 months ofÂ construction.</p> <p>The openingÂ of theÂ transformed iconic shopping mall from its once aged and dusty appearance reveals the vision of B+H Architects, who designedÂ the new shopping centre and surrounds for Rideau Street.</p> <p>B+HÂ has previously worked on the CIBC Pan Am/Parapan Am Aquatics Centre and Field House in Markham, Ont., northeast of Toronto, and Mosaic Stadium at Taylor Field in Regina, home of the Canadian Football League Roughriders.</p> <figure class=\"wp-caption post-img size_this_image_test aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_857830\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-857830\" src=\"http://wpmedia.ottawacitizen.com/2016/08/rideau-centre-photos-provided-by-publicist-katy-creates-from2.jpeg?quality=55&amp;strip=all\" alt=\"A redesigned concept of the Rideau Centre. (Provided by Katy Creates)\"><figcaption class=\"wp-caption-text wp-caption\"><span class=\"img-caption\"> A redesigned concept of the Rideau Centre. (Provided by Katy Creates)</span></figcaption></figure><p>According to B+H senior associate StÃ©phane Raymond, the Rideau Centre revitalization was allÂ about opening the dark and dreary walkways and shops within the mall to the Ottawa skyline and allowing more natural light to flood in.</p> <p>âThe Centre was first opened in 1983, and I think that was the late end of a certain style,â said Raymond, referring to the mallâs dark, artificially lit hallways.Â He said opening the exterior of the mall, which runs parallel toÂ Rideau Street, was difficult because retailers had to buy into the concept of bringing in natural light.</p> <div id=\"fsk_splitbox_1715\" class=\" fsk_splitbox_1715\"></div> <p>â<span class=\"s1\">Itâs challenging, because a lot of retailers prefer wall space to windows,â he said. â</span>Weâve renovated all of their existing facades, which you probably remember as being mostly pre-cast with not many windows out to the street. Thatâs all been replaced with a lot of glass. Itâs very open.â</p> <figure class=\"wp-caption post-img size_this_image_test aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_857834\"><img class=\"wp-image-857834 size-full\" src=\"http://wpmedia.ottawacitizen.com/2016/08/rideau-centre-photos-provided-by-publicist-katy-creates-from6.jpeg?quality=55&amp;strip=all\" alt=\"Rideau Centre photos provided by publicist Katy Creates from KG&amp;A for Vito's story on the architect. 0805 rideau Katy Creates Publicist katy@kimgraham.ca T. 416.537.0954 ext. 2320 M: 416.831.8129\"><figcaption class=\"wp-caption-text wp-caption\"><span class=\"img-caption\"> A design concept of the new Simons store at the Rideau Centre.</span></figcaption></figure><p>Raymond said the retailers have now embraced the idea, with many using the large windows to entice consumers to come inside. Some, such as Montreal clothier Simons, which is opening in the expansion, have even set up sitting areas and cafÃ©s which allow customers to sit and admire the view.</p> <p>The redesign, according to Raymond, is also aimed at tyingÂ in the new Rideau Centre with work soon to be completed on Rideau Street, which was closed last year to mostÂ passenger vehicle traffic and some buses as crews beganÂ revitalizing the street, creating a public park at Ogilvy Square and finishing the Rideau Street transit station, which will deliver passengers on the LRTâs new underground Confederation Line when it opens in 2018.</p> <p>The Bay, meanwhile, is undergoing its own renovation.</p> <p>The area is bordered by the ByWard Market and the University of Ottawa. Raymond said the plan was to create a propertyÂ that allows for flow through the area and encourages patrons to walk, rest or shop at their leisure.</p> <figure class=\"wp-caption post-img size_this_image_test aligncenter\" id=\"attachment_857831\"><img class=\"wp-image-857831 size-full\" src=\"http://wpmedia.ottawacitizen.com/2016/08/rideau-centre-photos-provided-by-publicist-katy-creates-from3.jpeg?quality=55&amp;strip=all\" alt=\"Rideau Centre photos provided by publicist Katy Creates from KG&amp;A for Vito's story on the architect. 0805 rideau Katy Creates Publicist katy@kimgraham.ca T. 416.537.0954 ext. 2320 M: 416.831.8129\"><figcaption class=\"wp-caption-text wp-caption\"><span class=\"img-caption\"> The new Rideau Centre set to open Wednesday.</span></figcaption></figure><p>Wednesdayâs opening offers a glimpse atÂ the future of Rideau Street,Â which has seen billions of dollars in investment over the past decade and is fuelling hopes of a retail revival in the heart of the city.</p> <p>ReconstructionÂ of the Rideau Centre involved the removal of several familiar tenants, the relocation of the food court, and theÂ addition of a fewÂ new retailers, with many opening their first shops in the nationâs capital.</p> <p>The aged cinema that once spanned the Rideau Centreâs fourth floor has been pulled down to accommodateÂ theÂ Simons store. The popular MarchÃ© restaurant vanished from its long-held space beneath the escalators on the mallâs first floor. Cinnabon is but a sweet memory, and the Sports Experts store near Rideau Street is closing its doors.</p> <p>The souped-up food court was moved about a year ago to a larger space filled with higher-end food offerings. In its old spot is a sleek, relocated Shoppers Drug Mart. Nordstrom now occupies the space once held byÂ Sears, and clothing retailer H&amp;M is opening its second Ottawa location at the mall.</p> <p>There will also be four new restaurants and 386 more parking spots.</p> <p>When the Rideau Centre broke ground inÂ 2013 on theÂ $360-million expansion and renovation, the plan includedÂ 230,000 square feet of new spaceÂ in theÂ four-storey shopping area on the site of the dilapidatedÂ Ogilvy Building, which hadÂ stood empty for 20 years prior its demolition.</p> </div>",
        "_id": "1",
