    "origin_url": "http://ottawacitizen.wpdev5.canada.com/entertainment/celebrity/another-test-story/wcm/26bafb66-09dd-4985-bcf1-f629cea63eb8",
    "status": "published",
    "titles": {
      "main": "Who's responsible when there's an injury on publicly accessible private land?"
    },
    "content_elements": [
      {
        "content": "The weekend drowning death of a 10-year-old boy at Constance Bay raises a troublesome question: who is legally responsible when such a tragedy occurs on a publicly-accessible property that is privately owned?",
        "_id": "1",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "The City of Ottawa has insisted that it doesn&acirc;t own Constance Bay&acirc;s beaches. Who owns them &acirc; and what it means for their use &acirc; has been a long battle in Constance Bay.",
        "_id": "2",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Ownership of The Point, a triangular piece of land that juts out into the Ottawa River, has been a convoluted footnote in that saga. In 2010, the City of Ottawa delivered a legal opinion that unlike most of other beaches at Constance Bay, beaches attached to properties at The Point belonged to the landowners.",
        "_id": "3",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "That legal opinion divided the village. One meeting attracted 150 people after residents posted signs reading: &acirc;No Stopping, No Alcohol, No Walking after Sunset.&acirc; Some argued that the signs were aimed at curtailing a right that residents had enjoyed for almost a century.",
        "_id": "4",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "&acirc;Ownership is a very complicated issue. It&acirc;s been around for decades,&acirc; said Angela Bernhardt, the president of the Constance and Buckham&acirc;s Bay Community Association. &acirc;It would be nice to get it settled once and for all.&acirc;",
        "_id": "5",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<div id=\"fsk_splitbox_1715\" class=\"  fsk_splitbox_1715\"></div>",
        "_id": "6",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<a href=\"http://wpmedia.ottawacitizen.com/2016/08/0810dw.jpg?quality=55&amp;strip=all\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-860376 size-full\" src=\"http://wpmedia.ottawacitizen.com/2016/08/0810dw.jpg?quality=55&amp;strip=all&amp;w=640\" alt=\"Dangerous waters\"></a>",
        "_id": "7",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Fran Dawson, who owns a property that includes beachfront near The Point, says interest in Constance Bay&acirc;s beaches have exploded since they have been featured on the Internet. The posts attract people, but they don&acirc;t warn about dangers, she says. &acirc;That&acirc;s a problem.&acirc;",
        "_id": "8",
        "paragraph": "close",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Visitors have started bonfires and left garbage and shattered glass for homeowners to clean up. Dawson, who is 78, has often spotted people and warned them herself about hazards, which include jagged clam shells as sharp as knives.",
        "_id": "9",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<h2 class=\"cat-head short\">Related</h2>",
        "_id": "10",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<ul class=\"related_links\">\n<li><a href=\"http://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/police-marine-unit-now-searching-for-body-of-10-year-old-boy-in-constance-bay-area\">Boy’s body recovered after apparent drowning in Constance Bay</a></li> <li><a href=\"http://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/a-history-who-owns-constance-bays-beaches\">A history: Who owns Constance Bay’s beaches?</a></li> <li><a href=\"http://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/drownings-at-constance-bay\">Why is Constance Bay so dangerous?</a></li> <li><a href=\"http://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/constance-bay-residents-call-for-action-after-10-year-old-drowns-in-ottawa-river\">Constance Bay residents call for action after 10-year-old drowns in Ottawa River</a></li> </ul>\n",
        "_id": "11",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Dawson worries about liability. Homeowners have put up signs, but these have been vandalized, she says. One family donated a warning sign with a concrete stand. It was dragged into the water and became a hazard itself. &acirc;Signs aren&acirc;t going to work,&acirc; she says.",
        "_id": "12",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "But she also doesn&acirc;t want to build a fence to keep people out. &acirc;We want the community to be able to walk on the beach. We feel it&acirc;s just as much theirs as ours.&acirc;",
        "_id": "13",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Legally speaking, the heart of the question is Ontario&acirc;s 1990 ",
        "_id": "14",
        "paragraph": "open",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "<a href=\"https://www.ontario.ca/laws/statute/90o02\">Occupiersâ Liability Act, </a>",
        "_id": "15",
        "type": "raw_html",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "which defines the &acirc;occupier&acirc; of a property. An occupier doesn&acirc;t necessarily have to be the owner.",
        "_id": "16",
        "paragraph": "close",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "University of Ottawa law professor Bruce Feldthusen, an expert in tort law, says landowners definitely meet the definition of &acirc;occupier&acirc; under the act. But ownership isn&acirc;t the key. An occupier can be a tenant, or someone who sits on a towel everyday on the beach. An &acirc;occupier&acirc; is anyone who assumes control.",
        "_id": "17",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "The City of Ottawa, for example, has placed temporary toilets and garbage containers near the beach.",
        "_id": "18",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "&acirc;If the city is doing things on the beach and they know it&acirc;s dangerous, you can argue that they&acirc;re an occupier,&acirc; says Feldthusen. &acirc;The more they do in relation to the land and water, the more the argument that they have control.&acirc;",
        "_id": "19",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "The next question is whether an occupier acted reasonably, he says. &acirc;Their duty is to take reasonable care. A warning sign isn&acirc;t an onerous obligation.&acirc;",
        "_id": "20",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "The community association has posted a signing indicating that the beach is not a City of Ottawa beach and warns &acirc;use at your own risk.&acirc; But Feldthusen says this kind of warning is &acirc;not ironclad.&acirc; The courts usually want a more explicit warning, pointing out dangers in the water, for example.",
        "_id": "21",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "About four years ago, a man in his 20s who was visiting a cottage community near Penetanguishene took a dive from the end of a communally-owned dock, not knowing the water was only three feet deep. The man suffered serious injuries and became a quadriplegic. He took legal action against all of the cottage owners &acirc; there were almost 200 &acirc; and the cottage owners&acirc; association.",
        "_id": "22",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "The case was settled out of court, but the lesson to be learned was that there can be more than one &acirc;occupier&acirc; of a property, says personal injury lawyer Troy Lehman. At the bare minimum, the cottage community should have erected a sign saying the water wasn&acirc;t deep enough to dive, he says.",
        "_id": "23",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "&acirc;Occupiers have a duty to warn visitors about known dangers that wouldn&acirc;t be apparent to a visitor,&acirc; said Lehman, who lives in a subdivision which has communal ownership of a trail. The homeowners maintain an insurance policy and put up warning signs about hazards.",
        "_id": "24",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "&acirc;If you own a communal property, you take a risk. But you can insure against it,&acirc; he says.",
        "_id": "25",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Bernhart says the community association has no opinion on the issue of beach ownership because its beyond the association&acirc;s jurisdiction. But the association feels that the beaches are a heritage resource and &acirc;supports the continued, respectful, traditional use of them by the community, based on good faith co-operation.&acirc;",
        "_id": "26",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Getting a final answer about ownership would mean going to court, she says. &acirc;And that would take time and money.&acirc;",
        "_id": "27",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
        "channels": [
          "desktop",
          "tablet",
          "phone"
        ]
      },
      {
        "content": "Asked who would be held legally liable for an accident that happened on &acirc;private&acirc; property that has long been used as a public resource, the city&acirc;s deputy solicitor David White responded: &acirc;The City would not be the appropriate contact for questions on occupier&acirc;s liability.&acirc;",
        "_id": "28",
        "paragraph": "wrap",
        "type": "text",
